description: This issue of the industriesâ top Golden Age reprint anthology as usual boasts a line-up of all-time great artists. Will Eisner illustrates an early adventure starring Yarko, Master Magician, as he faces âThe Voodoo Kingâ, Bob Powell contributes a Cave Girl tale called âThe Little Man Who Was All Thereâ. âGood Girl Artâ master Bill Ward brings the glamorous Torchy Todd to life in a hilarious case of mistaken identity while John Severin pits Billy The Kid up against âEl Chivitoâ. Joe Kubert delves into a world of horror in âThe Mirror Of Isisâ, while Murphy Anderson takes The Space Rangers on âThe Quest forb Lost Atlantisâ- plus a precode crime thriller âFatal Mistake!â drawn by Mort Meskin. The Mysterious Traveller tells the weird story of âThe Sultanâ by Steve Ditko. Rounding out this package is a 3 page love story by the guys who created the genre, Simon and Kirby, entitled âPlease Help Meâ. Superbly- reproduced full-story reprints covering a wide variety of story types, from publishers like Quality, Fox Features, Avon, Magazine Enterprises, Charlton, Fiction House and Prize Comics. 52 pages, black and white with color cover. Standard comic book format.

Another cavalcade of comicâs best creators of the 1940â²s and â50â²s, at work on a variety of story genres. Originally published by Avon Periodicals, Joe Kubert illustrates the eerie sci-fi/ horror thriller, âMap of Doom . Wally Wood and Joe Orlando team up to illustrate the Captain Science adventure, âThe Insidious Doctor Khartoum,â from Youthful Magazines. Then, originally seen in Fiction House Comicsâ Wings; itâs Jane Martin, masterfully drawn by the incomparable George Evans, followed by a Charlton S-F shorty by Steve Ditko, âAdrift in Spaceâ. John Buscema does the honors on a Western tale of the Desert Hawk entitled âWheel of Fortuneâ, from St. John Pubs; Bill Ward is reprised from his Quality Comics days with a madcap laugh-riot starring Torchy, and Mort Meskin illustrates the inexplicable âThe House That Tried To Kill Meâ, from Prize Comics. Black and white with a color cover; 48 pages, standard comic book format.

This special âweird fantasyâ issue spotlights many of the finest artists of the 1950â²s, including Jack Kirby,(âAfraid To Dreamâ âThe Girl Who Could Walk on Waterâ), Wally Wood, Bob Powell, (âThe Doomed Patrolâ), Steve Ditko, (âThe Man Who Could See Tomorrowâ), Dick Ayers, Bill Everettt, Reed Crandall anf Jack Kamen, (âGhost Patrolâ) in gripping fantasy dramas originally published by Fiction House, Charlton, Prize and others, in crystal-clear, full-story reprints. 52 pages, black and white with color covers, standard comic book size, printed in 2003.

Bob Lubbers is in the spotlight this issue with cover art and reprints of two Fiction House features from The Golden Age: Captain Wings and Firehair- plus an illustrated text article on his career. In addition, thereâs a Jane Martin story as illustrated by EC great George Evans, macabre mystery by Jack Kirby with âThe Big Huntâ from Prize Comics; touching romance by master Alex Toth in âTill We Meet Againâ, and Harlton science fiction drawn by Steve Ditko on âThe Secret of Captain Xâ. All full story exact reprints from comicsâ formative years. 52 pages, black & white with color covers, standard comic book format.

Ace artist JACK KIRBY, champ of the Golden Age is in the spotlight this issue with the touching story of a boxer who finds love in âThe Leather Pusherâ. Then, itâs a gritty Alex Toth crime drama, straight out of Lev Gleasonâs Crime And Punishment- âThe Armored Car Murdersâ. Al williamson is in a sci-fi showcase with âThe Strangers From Spaceâ, Bob Powell adds whimsical weirdness with âDisc Jockeyâ, Steve Ditko shows âImaginationâ, and Kurt Schaffenberger sends âA Falling Starâ. All that plus former EC great Bernard Krigstein illustrates âThe Vagrantâ, and Bill Benilus rings in with âHighjack On Alpha-7â³, from a late -run issue of Planet Comics. 52 pages, black and white with color cover, standard comic book size, printed in 2004.

Another great issue of the title that tries to keep comics images alive and vibrant in the digital age!! See the best artists of the Golden Age at their peak: Reed Crandall on the swashbuckling superhero known as The Firebrand! Joe Kubert illustrates Chuck (Crimebuster) Chandler in âGem of an Ideaâ!!Bob Powell delineates Red Hawk in âThe Man Who Rode The Moonlightâ!! Weird fantasy with Jack Kirby doing âThe Fourth Dimension Is A Many-Splattered Thingâ!! Steve Ditko offers up science fiction on âThe Heritageâ!! Alex Toth handles âWorking Girlâs Romanceâ , and Mort Meskin adds âSoft Touchâ. Great full-story Golden Age reprints from Quality, M. E. Prize, Charlton, Lev Gleason and more. Black & white with color covers, 52 pages, standard comic book size.

The comics world lost one if itâs icons with the recent passing of the great Alex Toth. This special spotlight issue focuses on the spectacular work he did between 1950 & 1960. Featured are rare full-story reprints including Buster Crabbe in âDark Of The Moonâ, from Buster Crabbe #2, and âThe Big Catchâ ( starring the cast of the â77 Sunset Stripâ detective TV series) from Four Color #1066;a profusely-llustrated article on Alexâs work on the Jimmy Wakely series, and an art gallery showcasing much of Tothâs best work on splash pages & covers. In addition, read AC publisher Bill Blackâs thoughts on his correspondance with Toth over the years. 48 pages, black & white with color covers; standard comic book size; saddle stitched.

There's no time for slacking these days as Yoh and his friends race to the rescue of their one-time rival Tao Ren! Ren's dad has strict ideas about how a Tao should behave, and Ren's recent rebellion has earned him a stay in the family dungeons. But Yoh's influence has already started to wear off on Ren, who now has a new weapon against his father's terror tactics, and a group of friends to back him up! But the Tao stronghold is a strange and dangerous place, full of fear and monsters. Will friendship be enough to counter the bloody Way of the Tao?

Featuring art and story byÂ Dexter's LaboratoryÂ creator Genndy Tartakovsky!

description: It should have been a simple mission for the men and women of Rogue Squadronâan easy search-and-rescue for a group of Bothan castaways forced down on Malrev 4. But when they got to the backwater planet, the Rogues found themselves first attacked by the Irrukiine, a doglike aboriginal race, and then by the Bothans themselves. There's some strange kind of hoodoo going down on Malrev 4âthis planet promotes madness and deceit, and not even the Rogues are immune!
name: Requiem for a Rogue, Part 2 of 4

description: The Bothan tourists that Wedge and crew have come to save are neither Bothans nor touristsâthey're a consortium of spies assigned to follow the Emperor. Wedge is glad to know this now, but he'd have been happier to have discovered this fact before his crew were trapped on this back-water planet called Malrev 4. Now Rogue Squadron is in the middle of a firing ground, between a twisted, self-styled "Lord of the Sith" who calls Malrev 4 his home and the leader of the spies, Girov, who desires the planet, its great temple, and all its power for his own!
name: Requiem for a Rogue, Part 3 of 4

description: Concluding the epic battle between the Rogue Squadron Rebels and the Sith-tainted Imperials! A member of Rogue Squadron makes the ultimate sacrifice in this concluding chapter of Requiem for a Rogue!
name: Requiem for a Rogue, Part 4 of 4

description: Wedge Antilles is the ace pilot of the Rebel Alliance, and his Rogue Squadron is the outfit of choice for every X-wing flyer. But just as the New Republic has its star space jockeys, so does the Empire. And Baron Fel and the Imperial 181st Fighter Division are hungry to see what Rogue Squadron is made of. Don't miss the comics premier of Baron Fel, the Empire's greatest fighter ace!
name: In the Empire's Service, Part 1 of 4

description: On the world of Brentaal, Imperial General Isoto prepares for a Rebel assault. His goal: not to save the planet, or even the Imperial base, but to save himself. Isoto has the best shield there is, the Empire's greatest fighter ace, Baron Fel. But having the Baron and having him take orders are two totally different things!
name: In the Empire's Service, Part 2 of 4

description: This non-fiction comic is a thorough resource on the entire solar system. It gives all the pertinent information about the planets (nine at the time of publication) and the Sun and Moon. It gives the size (radius, diameter and circumference) of every heavenly body. It gives the distance from each planet to the sun, the number of moons each planet has, its surface temperature for both day and night, and the chemical makeup of the atmosphere. It even covers the gravity issue, and tells how much one would weigh on the different planets and on the Moon. Some early astronomers are also covered, with comments on their discoveries. There's some interesting details, too. Pluto was named after its discoverer, Percival Lowell, in an odd way. The first two letters of the word Pluto are the initials of Percival Lowell. This book covers a lot in its pages.
name: To the Stars!

description: Printed in Norway in English, this issue was sold only at the United Nations

description:
In the wake of the death of the Emperor and the destruction of the Death Star II, a group of Rebel pilots are looking forward to some well-deserved R & R. Instead, they run into a deadly attack by vengeful Imperials that changes the course of all of their lives.

Rev up your engines-it's time for the Rogue Squadron to fly again! Join Luke Skywalker, Wedge Antilles, and the rest of the Rogues on a mission that will define them as heroes not just of the Rebellion, but as heroes for the whole galaxy!
name: Part One (of Three)

description:
On Wedge Antilles' home planet, Corellia, he and the other members of the Rogue Squadron are all that stand between an unarmed populace and a terrorist attack by remnants of Palpatine's Imperial forces.

Even the budding Jedi powers of Luke Skywalker won't be enough to tip the scales in the Rogues' favor, and to snatch victory from the jaws of this defeat may cost the life of one of their own!

High-flying action with the most popular heroes of the expanded Universe!
name: Part Two (of Three)

description:
Imperial terrorists have landed a devastating strike on Wedge Antilles'home planet and captured a member of Rogue Squadron. Now, Wedge and the rest of the Rogues are hot on their trail, determined to find their friend and bring these Imperial thugs to justice.

The fighting is fierce and the flying is faster in this whiz-bang conclusion to the series that defines the hottest heroes in the expanded Universe and launches an ace fighter squadron like none other in the galaxy!
name: Part Three (of Three)

description:
The tyranny has ended. But what will take its place? It is now five years after Return of the Jedi. Leia and Han are married and have shouldered heavy burdens in the government of the New Republic. And Luke Skywalker is the first in a hoped-for new line of Jedi Knights.

But thousands of light-years away, the last of the Emperor's warlords, Grand Admiral Thrawn, has taken command of the remains of the Imperial fleet. Thrawn has made two vital discoveries that could destroy the Rebel Alliance's New Republic. The tale that emerges is a towering epic of action, invention, mystery, and a spectacle of galactic scale -- in short, a story that is worthy of the name Star Wars.

volume.name: Star Wars: Heir to the Empire

description: Five years after the Empire's defeat in Return of the Jedi, the forces of the Empire have rallied. Even as Luke Skywalker searches for Jedi to join him in the inevitable battle, Grand Admiral Thrawn, the last of the Emperor's warlords, schemes with Joruus C'Baoth to end the battle before it can begin. Out-manned, out-numbered, and sorely out-gunned, Luke fears there is no hope. It's up to him to challenge Thrawn, the heir to the Empire.

volume.name: Star Wars: Heir to the Empire

description: When an Imperial assassin puts Leia in his cross-hairs, Chewbacca crosses the galaxy to take Leia to a place of safety. But there are things in the galaxy that are worse than being assassinated, and "safety" is only relative.

volume.name: Star Wars: Heir to the Empire

description: Luke Skywalker's Jedi senses have been struck blind! To make matters worse, Grand Admiral Thrawn has just arranged to receive a shipment of creatures capable of pushing back the power of the Force. Thrawns's purpose: to ambush Luke and turn him over to the dark Jedi Master, Joruus C'baoth!

volume.name: Star Wars: Heir to the Empire

description: Mara Jade has survived for most of her life among the worst riffraff in the galaxy. Years ago, she posed as a dancer in the decadent court of the late Jabba the Hutt. It was there that she first witnessed Luke's awesome powers of Jedi mind-control. Now, in the steaming jungles of Myrkr, Luke and Artoo are Jade's helpless captives. Jade is determined to finish off her Jedi prisoner -- once she's finished stripping him of his Jedi secrets!

volume.name: Star Wars: Heir to the Empire

description: Luke Skywalker has been bereft of the Force for some time now, and has had to rely on his wits and cunning to stay out of the hands of the Imperials. Now, disguised as a bounty hunter with the beautiful and lethal Mara Jade as his prisoner, he has to find Captain Talon Karrde, rescue Han from the Empire's clutches, and reunite with the other architects of the Rebellion. But even if Luke and Han prevail, the Rebellion may be on the verge of destruction, unraveling itself in a bloody civil war!

volume.name: Star Wars: Heir to the Empire

description: Jabba the Hutt lives to negotiate, and the art of the deal is his only discipline. But the goods he trades are the lives of others, and in that line of business you can't lose your head. These stories hold a valuable lesson: In a deal with the devil, you can always refuse. In a deal with Jabba, it's not advised. Follow his adventures into the seediest corners of the galaxy as he encounters vile gangsters, hungry princesses, and back-stabbing opportunists. You've seen how Jabba handles negotiations -- but how will he handle betrayal?
name: TPB

volume.name: Star Wars: Jabba The Hutt: The Art Of The Deal

description: Jabba has got a hot freighter on his hands and he's looking to unload it, quickly and discreetly. Enter Cabrool Nuum, a second-hand ship trader whose reputation for discretion is as long as his many years in the business. Unfortunately for Jabba, the years seem to have caught up with Cabrool, and his murderous offspring have taken advantage of the old man's dotage, just as they plan to take advantage of Jabba's impending arrival! In a seedy corner of the galaxy, on a planet of back-stabbing opportunists, Jabba the Hutt is about to land face first in The Dynasty Trap!

volume.name: Star Wars: Jabba The Hutt: The Dynasty Trap

description:
Beautiful twi'lek Jedi Aayla Secura goes undercover to ferret out a Separatist enclave. But when her cover is blown, Aayla finds herself going up against famed bounty hunter (and infamous Jedi killer) Aurra Sing!

This is the battle that Star Wars fans have been begging for, by the creative team that was born to bring it to them!

Plotted by Star Wars novelist Brian Daley (Han Solo at Stars' End) and written by See-Threepio actor Anthony Daniels and Droids writer Ryder Windham, with painted illustrations by Tales of the Marvels artist Igor Kordey. It's See-Threepio and Artoo-Detoo saving the planet Tahlboor, in an adventure set years before Star Wars: A New Hope! This prestige-format one-shot has it all.

It seems that Darth Krayt is at a loss. He has failed to turn Cade Skywalker over to the Dark Side. Cade just wants to be left to his own devices. He sides neither with the Jedi, nor with the Sith. So Darth Krayt orders his hand-picked few to attack Cade.

Now Cade is battling Darth Nihl. Cade knows that this is the being who killed his father. Still, he fights his darkest desires to keep himself from crossing over to the Dark Side. He severes Nihl's right arm with his lightsaber, but does not let him die. He heals him enough to let him live.

Krayt is not impressed with the proceedings. He proceeds to attack Cade.

Meanwhile, Morrigan Corde (who is secretly Cade's mom), arrives outside the Sith temple with Jariah and Deliah. She jumps from the Mynock and goes to find Cade.

A squadron of Imperial Tie Predators are alerted to the Mynock's presence and they come out to attack it. Moff Veed decrees so.

Krayt and Cade are engaged in a tough combat. Cade may not have many skills, but he trusts the Force, both light and dark, to carry him out of his opponent's attack range. Corde arrives outside a window and sees them battle. She blasts Krayt with her blaster and asks Cade to flee to safety. Cade attempts to jump out of the window. Krayt sees him and tells him that the jump will mean death. Cade jumps.

The Moffs have had a brief discussion and have called their Ties off from the attack on the Mynock. The hovering Mynock catches Cade in mid-air. Cade is relieved too meet his old friends. Corde escapes through the

undercity

.

Darth Krayt orders

Darth Wyyrlok

to find Cade.

Nyna Calixte and Morlish are chatting in her house. Morlish picks up a family heirloom belonging to the Skywalkers. Nyna takes it from and asks him to go. She activates it to reveal a hologram featuring Kol Skywalker, Morrigan Corde and young Cade.
name: Claws of the Dragon, Part Six

description: Final issue. Flight's End, Part 6 of 6. As the Netherworld's meta-humans go berserk, Hawkman and Hawkwoman clash with Count Viper to save the Netherworlders from his control. The Hawks succeed...but at a high and tragic price. Â
name: Flight's End, Part 6: Final Chapter

description: Before he was the ultimate power broker in the Marvel Universe, Norman Osborn was better known as the Green Goblin â the insane arch nemesis of everyoneâs friendly neighborhood Spider-Man! Now, experience an early turning point in the ongoing war between the wall-crawler and his glider-riding rival â the unmasking of Norman Osborn from AMAZING SPIDER-MAN #39-40 (1966) â like youâve never seen it before, fully remastered with modern coloring. Also featuring an all-new framing sequence and a Saga-style recap of the complete history of the Green Goblin!

They've been responsible for some of the most dazzling and awe-inspiring visuals ever put to film, and now the concept artists behind the Episode III: Revenge of the Sith bring their considerable talents to comics. The gifted minds of the Lucasfilm art department and the visual effects powerhouse Industrial Light & Magic come together to tell their own Star Wars tales in this compilation of short stories. Given free reign to explore any and every aspect of the Star Wars universe, each artist offers a new twist or a deeper view into that galaxy far, far away.

Nowhere else will you find a more pure or more different look at George Lucas' enduring creation than through the eyes of the Star Wars: Visionaries.
